The background of the seal is dark blue and white encircling the Dominican watchword, VERITAS which means Truth. A Martinian is formed to be a lover of truth, the search through study and prayer, to live and share the truth through service especially with the poor and needy. The inner core of the seal is a Cross, the symbol of our salvation brought by Christ, the person after whose image and likeness the Catholic school seeks to form .the SMPCS graduate. The circle that encapsulizes the entire picture represent the total formation, the dynamic and quality education which SMPCS promotes. The seal as a whole, signifies the role of SMPCS as center for integral evangelization in the Diocese of Malolos.
THE LIFE OF ST. MARTIN DE PORRES Martin was born on December 9, 1579 in Lima , Peru. His father Don Juan de Porres was Spanish noble and his mother Anna Velasquez was a freed Negro woman from Panama. Martin grew up in utter poverty anf cultivated an immense love for the poor afflicted . At the age of 12, " the little mulatto" apprenticed himself to a man who was a barber, pharmacist and surgeon. He worked diligently and soon came to be loved by the inmates of the city hospitals and prison among whom he distributed a part of his meager wages. After a few years of apostolate among the poor and sick, Martin asked his mother permission to enter the Dominican Monastery of the Most Holy Rosary. His mother consented and he applied as a lay-helper. He was welcomed into the monastery. He spent many night hours in spiritual reading, prayer and penitential exercises. Though he tried to hide the miraculous favors which God bestowed upon him, he soon came to be regarded as a saint and angel of peace and compassion. He was able to heal the sick by his mere touch, by his prayers, by the Sign of the Cross. He had gift of prophecy and invisibility; he could read people's heart and understand unexpressed desire even at grest distances. Although he never left Lima, there was several authenticated cases of his having personally assisted those in sickness and distress in Mexico, Algiers, Frane, the Philippines, China and Japan. Martin was full of zeal for his vacation and never stopped to thank God for the great privilege of becoming one of his followers. He lived off almost constant prayers, and his charity, humility and obedience were extraordinary. At 60, Martin became ill and it was on the evening of November 3,1693 when he went to his eternal reward. Pope john XXIII raised Martin de Porres to the altar of the church on May 5,1962. He is the Patron Saint of Social Justice and the Father of the poor, the sick and the needy.
VISION - MISSION STATEMENT
St. Martin de Porres Catholic School of Paombong envisions a school community educated in the faith, living and proclaiming the Gospel through prayer, stuy and service to the poor as exemplified by its Patron, St. Martin de Porres and revitalized by a special devotion to the Holy Eucharist, to the Blessed Virgin Mary and St. James the Apostle, the Patron Saint of the Parish.
Inspired by this vision, we commit ourselves to provide quality education and to work for integral evangelization for the total formation of the entire school community into a truly Catholic, integral and service-oriented persons.
PRE-SCHOOL OBJECTIVES
1. To present models for imitation that will make the pupil see GOD as a Father and all people and things around him as gifts.
2. To employ learning experience that will allow him to think and do things independently within the limits of his maturity.
3. To provide opportunities that will inspire him to practice desirable social behavior in his relation with other children as well as with adults.
4. To use experiential approaches which will help him manifest psychomotor coordinator for effective performance befitting his age.
5. To provide learning opportunities that will allow him to manifest reading readiness in English and Filipino.
6. To develop basic skill in numeracy.
GRADE SCHOOL OBJECTIVES
1. To use experiential approaches which will enable the child to acknowledge God as the Father and Creator, Jesus as Brother and Redeemer, the Holy Spirit as Sanctifier with Mar as Mother, and persons as brothers and sisters in the Lord.
2. To provide the basic knowledge and develop the foundational skills, attitudes and values, including his moral and spiritual dimensions essential to the child’s personal development and necessary for the living in and contributing to a developing and changing social milieu.
3. To provide learning experiences which increase the child’s awareness of and responsiveness to the changes in society, and prepare him for constructive and effective involvement.
4. To promote and intensity the child’s knowledge of identification with, and love for the nations and the people to which he belongs.
5. To promote work experiences which develop and enhance the child’s orientation to the world of work and creativity in order to prepare him to engage in honest and gainful work.
